{"cursor":"2484","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Hajiya Bilkisu Salisu Ahmed Funtuwa' is a Nigerian author. She writes novels in\nHausa that focus on female Muslim protagonists. {{cite book\n  | last = Sheldon first = Kathleen E authorlink = coauthors = title =\n  | Historical dictionary of women in Sub-Saharan Africa publisher = Scarecrow\n  | Press year = 2005 location = pages = 88 url =\n  | http://books.google.com/?id=36BViNOAu3sC doi = id = isbn =0-8108-5331-0 }}\n She is one of the best known writers of what is known as \"Kano\nmarket literature\" or Littattafan Soyayya â \"books of love\". {{Cite journal\n  | last = Whitsitt first = Novian author-link = title = Islamic-Hausa Feminism\n  | Meets Northern Nigerian Romance: The Cautious Rebellion of Bilkisu Funtuwa\n  | journal = African Studies Review volume = issue = pages = date = April 2003\n  | year = url =\n  | http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4106/is_200304/ai_n9219184/ doi = id\n  | = accessdate = 2009-07-30 postscript = .}}\n Her novels combine themes of feminism and women's rights with issues\nrelating to the Hausa people and Islam, drawing from her own experiences as a\nmember of these groups. {{cite web\n  | last = Sheme first = Ibrahim authorlink = coauthors = title = Bilkisu\n  | Funtuwa Interview work = publisher = Bahaushe Mai Ban Haushi! blog date =\n  | 2007-04-07 url = http://ibrahim-sheme.blogspot.com/2007/04/bilkisu-funtuwa-\n  | interview.html doi = accessdate =2009-07-30 }}\n Funtuwa lives with her family in Funtua, Katsina State, Nigeria.\n","linknr":112,"url":"Bilkisu_Funtuwa","recorded":1375079899,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bilkisu_Funtuwa&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Bilkisu_Funtuwa&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?deb